Rules and Ethics\n|Member\n|-\n|Joint Committee; Finance; Public Safety (inactive)\n|Member\n|}\n\nAlthough he was not able to achieve a majority of votes in the February 27, 2007 general election, he was re-elected in the April 17 runoff election against his challenger Leroy Jones.\n\nBrookins made $114,913 as a part-time alderman in 2011, making him one of the 19 highest paid alderman.  While others chose not to accept annual pay raises while city employees were laid off, Brookins did stating, \"Once it's out there, I think for me to give it back to the city for someone else to waste it somewhere else in the city doesn't make sense, and it doesn't help me with my obligations to my family.\"  An additional source of revenue for Alderman Brookins is his law firm.<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/ct-met-chicago-aldermen-salaries-20120130,0,2113353.story</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2014, Brookins' chief of staff, Curtis V. Thompson Jr. was charged with accepting a $7,500 bribe as part of an undercover corruption probe,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/politics/former-brookins-aide-reveals-he-tried-to-help-feds-ensnare-21st-ward-alderman/|title=Former Brookins aide reveals he tried to help feds 'ensnare' 21st Ward alderman|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref> and sentenced to 15 months in prison bu U. S. district [[Samuel Der-Yeghiayan|Judge Samuel Der-Yeghiayan]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/ct-alderman-brookins-aide-sentenced-met-20150527-story.html|title=Ex-aide to Ald. Brookins gets 15 months in prison for bribery|last=Meisner|first=Jason|newspaper=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref> The [[Chicago Sun-Times|Chicago Sun]] reports that \"Thompson helped a federal informant land Brookins' essential support for a liquor license in the 21st Ward in 2013. In exchange, the informant handed Thompson 75 $100 bills stuffed into a Christmas card during a party at Brookins' office, court records show.\"<ref>http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/local/breaking/chi-fbi-aldermans-chief-of-staff-charged-with-bribery-20140228,0,5504109.story</ref>\n\nOn November 13, 2016, Brookins was biking along Cal-Sag Trail when a [[squirrel]] jumped into the spokes, and crashed the bike. This left Brookins with a fractured skull, broke his nose, and knocked out a few teeth. The attack came after Brookins had given a series of speeches denouncing squirrels in Chicago saying \"It's a pet peeve. It does invoke some giggles. But we are spending too much money on replacing garbage carts because the squirrels continue to eat through 'em,\" and \"I get calls [with residents saying], 'I need a new garbage can.' I just gave you a garbage can. [And the caller says], 'Well, the squirrels ate through it in two days and nobody wants trash throughout the community. So they keep asking us for garbage cans.\" A survey found that 11% of the cities garbage carts are damaged, costing $300,000 in repairs. At least some of that damage does come from squirrels. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://chicago.suntimes.com/news/alderman-says-aggressive-squirrels-eating-through-garbage-carts/|title=Alderman says 'aggressive squirrels' eating through garbage carts|newspaper=Chicago Sun-Times|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2016/11/22/suicide-bomber-squirrel-hospitalizes-chicago-politician-who-spoke-out-against-squirrels/|title='Suicide bomber' squirrel hospitalizes Chicago politician who spoke out against squirrels|website=Washington Post|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chicagoinc/ct-brookins-squirrels-1122-chicago-inc-20161121-story.html|title=Kamikaze squirrel gets revenge on Ald. Brookins|last=Janssen|first=Kim|newspaper=chicagotribune.com|access-date=2016-12-11}}</ref>\n\nOn December 1, 2017, Brookins announced that he was circulating petitions to challenge U.S. Congressman Bobby L. Rush of Chicago's Second Congressional District, but Brookins later withdrew his petitions when Rush ultimately filed to keep his seat, on December 4, 2017.  But three days later, on December 7, 2017, Brookins announced his intent to \"leave public service\" by circulating petitions to fill a vacancy on the Circuit Court of Cook County when the Illinois Courts Commission forced former-judge Valarie Turner into retirement.  On January 30, 2018, the Cook County Electoral Board removed Brookins from the ballot for that judicial vacancy after it was determined that Brookins was between 250 to 398 short of the required signatures to get on the ballot.<ref>chicagotribunecloutstreetJanuary30,2018</ref>\n\nIn the runoff of the [[2019 Chicago mayoral election]], Brookins endorsed [[Toni Preckwinkle]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcchicago.com/blogs/ward-room/chicago-mayor-race-endorsements-507305521.html |title=List of Endorsements in the Race for Chicago Mayor |publisher=NBC Chicago |date= |accessdate=April 2, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBrookins is married to Ebony Taylor-Brookins. He has two children, Howard Brookins III, and Harrison.<ref>[http://www.aldermanhowardbrookinsjr.com/about.html Alderman Howard B. Brookins Jr.: Ablut Alderman Brookins<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\nhttp://prev.dailyherald.com/story/?id=125243\n\nhttp://chicago.suntimes.com/news-chicago/7/71/639649/ex-chief-staff-ald-brookins-sentenced-15-months-prison\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235252/http://www.civicfootprint.org/geography/ward/21 CivicFootprint: 21st ward]\n*[http://vimeo.com/album/167495 Video \"Run for Cook County States Attorney\"]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150125035102/http://www.howardbrookinsjr.com/ Alderman Howard Brookins Jr. Website]\n\n{{Chicago City Council}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brookins, Howard}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category: